questions.text:
What is the output of this code?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int x = 10;
    int y = 3;
    std::cout << x / y << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

What does the `&` in this function signature mean?

```cpp
void increment(int& value) {
    value++;
}

int main() {
    int n = 5;
    increment(n);
    std::cout << n;  // ???
}
```

questions.explanation:
In a **parameter type**, `&` declares a **reference** â€” an alias for the caller's variable. Changes through the reference modify the original:

```cpp
void increment(int& value) {
    value++;  // modifies the caller's variable directly
}

int n = 5;
increment(n);
std::cout << n;  // 6
```

Without `&`, the function would receive a copy and `n` would remain `5`.

